# Architecture Repo Agent Rules

## NON-NEGOTIABLE rules (absolute, never override)

- **NO_SECRETS_IN_GIT**: Zero plaintext or base64-encoded secrets, passwords, tokens, API keys, or credentials of any kind in any file committed to any git repository. All secrets live in Vault, delivered via `ExternalSecret` or `PushSecret`. Violating this rule is an immediate blocking issue.
- **NO_DELETE_SOVEREIGN_NS**: Never delete any namespace prefixed `sovereign-*`. Deletion of these namespaces is permanently prohibited.
- **DEPLOY_AFTER_PHASE**: After completing each phase of work: commit all changes, push to remote, trigger an ArgoCD sync. No phase is complete without a deployed and healthy state.
- **ARGOCD_ONLY_POST_INIT**: After `make init-central-argo`, all subsequent cluster changes must flow through ArgoCD. Direct YAML application (`oc apply`) is forbidden for configuration changes.

## Constraints

- **Mermaid diagrams** — all architecture diagrams must use Mermaid syntax in code blocks.
- **Small diagrams** — max ~15 nodes per diagram. Split complex topics into multiple focused diagrams.
- **No large files** — any file above 500 lines must be split into multiple files.
- **Simple language** — documentation should be understandable by non-technical stakeholders where possible.
- **No secrets** — never write real tokens, passwords, API keys. Use `<placeholder>`.
- **Follow architecture** — `docs/` directory is the source of truth for platform topology.
- **Always update docs** — after any architectural, topology, or component change, update the relevant files in `docs/`.
- **Hardening checks** — at the end of each work cycle, perform hardening checks and update or add entries in `hardeningcheck/`. Each new platform component must have its own hardening check file.
- **Commit freely** — push to main at any time.
- **Keep in sync** — any topology change in `bootstrap/` must be reflected here.
- **No git history** — never use git log, git blame, or commit history for context. Only look at current file state.

## Platform Components (actual, not aspirational)

### Central Cluster Only
- ArgoCD (OpenShift GitOps) — central cluster, self-heal + prune enabled
- RHACM (MultiClusterHub) — central cluster, manages services cluster
- Vault — central cluster, secrets management, standalone mode
- External Secrets Operator — central cluster, syncs Vault secrets to K8s
- Vault ClusterSecretStore — central cluster, connects ESO to Vault
- Gitea — central cluster, self-hosted Git service

### Both Clusters
- Keycloak (RHBK) — both clusters, HA mode, operator from certified catalog
- ACS (RHACS) — **disabled** (`enabled: false` in app-of-apps)
- ODF / Noobaa — both clusters, S3-compatible object storage
- Quay Registry — both clusters, enterprise container registry
- Crunchy Postgres for Kubernetes — both clusters, certified operator from certified-operators catalog

### Namespace Topology
- **Central cluster**: `sovereign-cloud-jobs`, `sovereign-cloud-helpers`
- **Services cluster**: `sovereign-cloud`, `sovereign-cloud-plugins`

### Services Cluster Only
- AAP (Ansible Automation Platform) — services cluster, controller + EDA + hub
- Entity Operator — services cluster, provisions tenant namespaces from Entity CRs
- Plugin RBAC Operator — services cluster, manages Keycloak group RBAC bindings
- Plugin Vault Operator — services cluster, deploys dedicated Vault instances per tenant
- Sovereign Dashboard — services cluster, entity management UI
- Tenancy Dashboard — services cluster, tenant-scoped RBAC + Vault management UI
- All `hybridsovereign.redhat` operators — services cluster (mandatory rule)

### Operator Placement Rules
- **`hybridsovereign.redhat` operators** → always on the **services cluster** (Entity Operator, plugin_rbac, etc.)
- **`helper.hybridsovereign.redhat` operators** → always on the **central cluster** (future additions)

### External
- OCI Registry (Quay) — external, stores Helm charts + images, robot has read-only access
- ApplicationSet — drives app-of-apps pattern from central cluster

### Platform Automation
- Ansible Runner — container image for platform automation jobs
- Sovereign Jobs — Ansible jobs for Keycloak, Vault, Gitea configuration

## ArgoCD rules

- All Applications must have `selfHeal: true` and `prune: true`.
- ArgoCD must always be fully in sync. If not, investigate and fix.
- Enable dynamic plugins when available.
- There is ONE app-of-apps chart (`helm/central/`) for BOTH clusters. No `helm/services/` directory.
- All services cluster configs are deployed by central ArgoCD using `destination.server` targeting the services cluster URL.

## NON-NEGOTIABLE: ArgoCD and cluster interaction rules

1. **NEVER create `kind: ApplicationSet` on the services cluster.**
2. **NEVER create `kind: Application` on the services cluster.**
3. All management of services cluster goes through central ArgoCD with `destination.server`.
4. **ACM is ONLY on the central cluster** — never on services.
5. **Only interact with ArgoCD on central cluster** — never query, create, or modify ArgoCD resources on services.
6. **All deployments via central ArgoCD** — no direct deployments outside of `make` bootstrap targets.
7. **AppProject separation**: `project: central` for central resources, `project: services` for services resources.
8. **`oc` client**: investigation + resource deletion + ArgoCD sync/refresh on central only. Never for YAML creation or `oc exec`.

## Documentation rules

- All documentation lives in `docs/technical/` (developer/operators) and `docs/concepts/` (non-technical/managers/presentations).
- Technical docs: implementation details, step-by-step guides, CLI commands.
- Concepts docs: high-level overviews, simple diagrams, presentation-friendly format.

## OCI / Quay rules

- Robot account has **read-only** access on all repositories.
- Admin token used for write operations (repo creation, chart/image push).

## Keycloak rules

- Central cluster: realm `sovereign-central`, client `sovereign-central`
- Services cluster: realm `sovereign-tenants`, client `sovereign-tenants-services`
- Group `sovereign-admin` = cluster-admin on both clusters
- Secrets stored in Vault KV `central/keycloak-clients`, delivered via External Secrets

## Vault rules

- Two Vault clusters: `vault-central` (central cluster) and `vault-services` (services cluster), both in `vault` namespace
- **HA Raft mode, 3 replicas** — NOT standalone
- Initialized via sovereign-jobs Ansible playbooks (vault-init, vault-services-init)
- KV v2 engine `central/` on vault-central — single source of truth for all platform secrets
- Unseal keys + root tokens stored in k8s Secret `vault-init-secrets` AND backed up in `vault-central` namespace via ExternalSecret
- **Authentication**: ESO uses Kubernetes auth (not root token). Humans use Keycloak OIDC.
- `kubernetes-central` mount on vault-central: for central cluster workloads
- `kubernetes-services` mount on vault-central: for services cluster workloads
- `sovereign-admin` Keycloak group maps to `sovereign-admin-policy` (full access) on both vaults
